hts.** Class A cannot remove a Class B Director even with unanimous Class A support; only Class B, voting separately as a class, can do so. Conversely, Class B participates (with 10× weighting) in the combined-class vote to remove Common Stock Directors. So Class A\'s influence over its own 49% block is also subject to Class B\'s 10× voting power on the combined-class vote.\\n\\n4. **Practical governance consequence.** A Class A shareholder with a majority of economic interest is, in board-composition terms, a **permanent minority**. Economic ownership confers no corresponding ability to determine — or even to influence through ordinary voting — the majority of the board. This is materially more entrenching than a conventional 10-vote/1-vote dual-class structure, where economic majority (above the ~90.9% threshold) would at least theoretically confer full board control.\\n\\nIn short: SpaceX\'s structure converts what would otherwise be a *proportional, dilutable, threshold-dependent* founder lock (the conventional 10-vote model) into an *absolute, dilution-proof, threshold-free* lock on a board majority. For a Class A shareholder, holding a majority of the economic interest is **economically real but governance-irrelevant** with respect to the majority of the board — the separate-class election of the Class B Directors is the dispositive mechanism, not the 10-vote multiplier.\\n\\n---\\n\\n{\\n  \\"sources\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Charter provisions on Class A/Class B voting rights, director elections (Class B Directors and Common Stock Directors), removal and vacancy-filling, Class B protective provisions, and controlled-company disclosure\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## How SpaceX\'s Dual-Mechanism Voting Structure Differs from a Conventional 10-Vote/1-Vote Dual-Class Structure\n\n### 1. The Two Structures Compared\n\n**Conventional 10-vote/1-vote dual-class structure (all directors elected by combined class vote):**\n- Class B = 10 votes/share; Class A = 1 vote/share.\n- All directors are elected by Class A and Class B voting *together as a single class*, with each share weighted by its vote multiplier.\n- Class B\'s control of the board is therefore *contingent and proportional*: it depends on Class B maintaining enough economic ownership relative to Class A so that 10× its stake exceeds Class A\'s stake.\n\n**SpaceX\'s dual-mechanism structure (per the S-1 charter provisions):**\n- Class B = 10 votes/share; Class A = 1 vote/share; Class C = 0 votes.\n- **Mechanism (i):** Class B, *voting separately as a class*, elects **51% of the total authorized directors** (the "Class B Directors"), rounded up, "for so long as any shares of Class B common stock remain outstanding."\n- **Mechanism (ii):** Class A and Class B, *voting together as a single class*, elect the remaining directors (the "Common Stock Directors") and decide all general shareholder matters.\n- Class B Directors may be removed only by a majority of Class B voting *separately as a class*; vacancies in Class B seats may be filled only by Class B or the remaining Class B Directors, "and not any other persons."\n- Class B also has separate-class veto rights over charter amendments affecting Class B rights and over certain mergers/combinations, plus the right to approve removal of Musk as CEO/Chairman.\n\n### 2. Economic Differences\n\n**(a) Absolute vs. proportional board control.** In a conventional 10-vote structure, Class B\'s grip on the board is a *function of its economic stake*. Class A can mathematically overcome Class B\'s 10× multiplier if Class A accumulates more than ~90.9% of the economic interest (the breakeven at which 1 × f > 10 × (1 − f), i.e., f > 10/11). Above that threshold, Class A — despite the 10× disadvantage — could elect the entire board.\n\nIn SpaceX\'s structure, the 51% Class B Director block is **not a function of relative economic ownership at all**. The 10-vote multiplier is *irrelevant* to that 51% block; what matters is the separate-class election mechanism. So long as a single Class B share remains outstanding, Class B elects 51% of the board regardless of whether Class A holds 10%, 50%, 90%, or 99.99% of the economic interest. There is no economic threshold Class A can cross to capture those seats.\n\n**(b) Immunity to dilution.** In a conventional structure, issuing additional Class A shares dilutes Class B\'s voting percentage and can eventually erode its board control. In SpaceX\'s structure, the 51% Class B Director block is **immune to dilution** — equity issuances of Class A (or Class C) cannot reduce Class B below 51% of the board so long as any Class B share is outstanding. The economic/voting decoupling is structural, not arithmetic.\n\n**(c) Redundancy of the 10× multiplier for board control.** In SpaceX\'s design, the 10-vote-per-share feature does the work only for: (i) electing the 49% Common Stock Directors, (ii) general shareholder matters, and (iii) removal of Common Stock Directors. For the 51% Class B Director block, the 10× feature is essentially redundant — the separate-class election is what delivers control. This makes SpaceX\'s structure a *stronger* entrenchment device than a pure high-vote dual class, because it layers an absolute class-vote lock on top of the proportional 10× multiplier.\n\n### 3. Practical Differences\n\n| Dimension | Conventional 10-vote/1-vote (combined vote for all directors) | SpaceX dual-mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Class B board control | Proportional to economic stake × 10 | Absolute 51% block, independent of economic stake |\n| Class A path to board majority | Theoretical: accumulate >~90.9% of economic interest | None, so long as any Class B share is outstanding |\n| Effect of Class A dilution of Class B | Can erode Class B control | No effect on Class B\'s 51% block |\n| Removal of Class B-affiliated directors | Combined class vote (subject to 10× weighting) | Class B only, voting separately as a class |\n| Vacancy filling for Class B seats | Combined class vote | Class B or remaining Class B Directors only — "not any other persons" |\n| Hostile-takeover immunity | Conditional (acquirer could cross the ~90.9% threshold) | Effectively absolute for the board majority |\n\n### 4. Specific Implication for a Class A Shareholder Holding a Majority of Economic Interest\n\nEven if Class A shareholders collectively held a **majority — indeed, even a supermajority — of the economic interest** in SpaceX, their ability to influence board composition would be **structurally capped at the 49% Common Stock Director block**. Specifically:\n\n1. **No path to a board majority.** Class A cannot elect, remove, or replace any Class B Director under any circumstance while Class B shares remain outstanding. Class A\'s maximum achievable board representation is the Common Stock Directors (49% of the board, rounded down). A Class A economic majority therefore **cannot translate into board control** — the economic interest and board control are decoupled for the majority of seats.\n\n2. **No leverage through accumulation.** Unlike a conventional 10-vote structure, where a Class A shareholder could in principle buy enough shares to outvote Class B on director elections, in SpaceX\'s structure **no amount of Class A accumulation changes the 51% Class B block**. The only route to influencing those seats is conversion/elimination of Class B shares, which itself requires Class B\'s separate-class consent (and is further protected by the Class B protective provisions on charter amendments and certain mergers).\n\n3. **Asymmetric removal rights.** Class A cannot remove a Class B Director even with unanimous Class A support; only Class B, voting separately as a class, can do so. Conversely, Class B participates (with 10× weighting) in the combined-class vote to remove Common Stock Directors. So Class A\'s influence over its own 49% block is also subject to Class B\'s 10× voting power on the combined-class vote.\n\n4. **Practical governance consequence.** A Class A shareholder with a majority of economic interest is, in board-composition terms, a **permanent minority**. Economic ownership confers no corresponding ability to determine — or even to influence through ordinary voting — the majority of the board. This is materially more entrenching than a conventional 10-vote/1-vote dual-class structure, where economic majority (above the ~90.9% threshold) would at least theoretically confer full board control.\n\nIn short: SpaceX\'s structure converts what would otherwise be a *proportional, dilutable, threshold-dependent* founder lock (the conventional 10-vote model) into an *absolute, dilution-proof, threshold-free* lock on a board majority. For a Class A shareholder, holding a majority of the economic interest is **economically real but governance-irrelevant** with respect to the majority of the board — the separate-class election of the Class B Directors is the dispositive mechanism, not the 10-vote multiplier.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Charter provisions on Class A/Class B voting rights, director elections (Class B Directors and Common Stock Directors), removal and vacancy-filling, Class B protective provisions, and controlled-company disclosure"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
